 style|Boston Red Sox|border=2}}; |Level!! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Boston Red Sox|border=2}}; |Team!! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Boston Red Sox|border=2}}; |League !! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Boston Red Sox|border=2}}; |Location\n|-\n|[[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]]||[[Pawtucket Red Sox]]||[[International League]]||[[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]]\n|-\n|[[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]]||[[Portland Sea Dogs]]||[[Eastern League (U.S. baseball)|Eastern League]]||[[Portland, Maine]]\n|-\n|[[Class A-Advanced]]||[[Salem Red Sox]]||[[Carolina League]]||[[Salem, Virginia]]\n|-\n|[[Class A (baseball)|Class A]]||[[Greenville Drive]]||[[South Atlantic League]]||[[Greenville, South Carolina]]\n|-\n|[[Class A-Short Season]]||[[Lowell Spinners]]||[[New York\u2013Penn League]]||[[Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Rookie-level|Rookie]]||[[Gulf Coast League Red Sox|GCL Red Sox]]||[[Gulf Coast League]]||[[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|-\n|[[Dominican Summer Red Sox|DSL Red Sox]]||[[Dominican Summer League]]||[[Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic]]\n|}\n\n==Other notable seasons and team records==\n{{main|List of Boston Red Sox team records}}\n*[[Nomar Garciaparra]] hit .372 in 2000, the club record for a right-handed hitter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/g/garcino01.shtml |title=Nomar Garciaparra Statistics&nbsp;\u2014 Baseball-Reference.com|author=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |work= }}</ref>\n*David Ortiz set the franchise record for home runs in a season with 54 in 2006, surpassing Jimmie Foxx's record of 50 home runs set in 1938.<ref>https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/BOS/leaders_bat_season.shtml</ref>\n*On April 22, 2007, Manny Ram\u00edrez, J. D. Drew, Mike Lowell, and Jason Varitek hit four consecutive home runs in the 3rd inning off 10 pitches from [[Chase Wright]] of the New York Yankees in his second Major League start and his fourth above Single-A ball. This was the fifth time in Major League history, and first time in Red Sox history this feat has occurred. Notable is that J. D. Drew had previously contributed to a four consecutive home run sequence on September 18, 2006 (coincidentally also the second batter in the sequence) while with the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]. Additionally, then-Red Sox manager Terry Francona's father, [[Tito Francona]], also was a part of such a four consecutive home run sequence for the [[Cleveland Indians]] in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070422&content_id=1925045&vkey=news_bos&fext=.jsp&c_id=bos|title=Sox tie mark with four straight homers &#124; redsox.com: News|accessdate=June 18, 2010}}</ref>\n*The overall regular season winning percentage since club inception in 1901 is .516, a record of 8595\u20138065 for games played through July 9, 2008. They started 2007 with winning percentage of .512 (8444\u20137960).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/ |title=Baseball Teams and Baseball Team Encyclopedias \u2014 |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref>\n* On September 1, 2007, Clay Buchholz no-hit the [[2007 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]] in his second Major League start. He is the first Red Sox rookie and 17th Red Sox pitcher to throw a no-hitter.<ref>[http://insider.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3001530&name=Neyer_Rob ESPN.com&nbsp;\u2014 Blogs&nbsp;\u2014 Rob Neyer Blog<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*On September 22, 2007, with a victory over the [[2007 Tampa Bay Devil Rays season|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]], the Red Sox clinched a spot in the postseason for the fourth time in five years, the first time in club history this has happened. Also, with this postseason berth, manager Terry Francona becomes the first manager in team history to lead the club to three playoff appearances.\n*Between May 15, 2003 and April 10, 2013, the Red Sox sold out every home game. The 820 game streak is a record for all major American sports, narrowly passing the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] record of 814 between 1977 and 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/redsox/story/2012-04-19/Fenway-Park-100th-anniversary/54422780/1|newspaper=USA Today|title=Happy Birthday: Fenway Park turns 100 years old|date=April 20, 2012|first=Seth|last=Livingstone}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Edes|first=Gordon|title=Red Sox's sellout streak ends|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/mlb/story/_/id/9158007/boston-red-sox-820-game-sellout-streak-ends|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=November 3, 2013}}</ref> The previous major league baseball record had been held by the Cleveland Indians, who sold out 455 games between June 12, 1995 and April 2, 2001. (The team's definition of a sellout: \"The criteria used for a sellout at Fenway Park have been the same since the early 1990s,\" Kennedy said in an e-mail. \"Our policy is simple and straightforward, and is used by many MLB clubs [and other sports teams around the country]. A sellout occurs when the number of tickets distributed to spectators is equal to or greater than the seating capacity at Fenway Park. [The 2008 seating capacity is 36,984 for day games and 37,400 for night games.]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080904&content_id=3417965&vkey=news_bos&fext=.jsp&c_id=bos&partnerId=rss_bos|title=Red Sox to set MLB sellout record|accessdate=July 28, 2009|date=September 4, 2008|first=Ian|last=Browne|work=MLB.com}}</ref> That is: a sellout only covers ticket sales, not spectators in physical seats.)[[File:President Trump Welcomes the Boston Red Sox to the White House (47028933704).jpg|thumb|Red Sox at the [[White House]] with [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] on May 9, 2019]]\n*On May 21, 2011, the Red Sox played against the Chicago Cubs at Fenway Park for the first time since the 1918 World Series (they had faced each other at Chicago's Wrigley Field in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2005/B06100CHN2005.htm|title=Chicago Cubs 14, Boston Red Sox 6|work=Retrosheet|publisher=Retrosheet.org|date=June 10, 2005}}</ref>). Both teams wore uniforms that matched the style worn in 1918.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2011/05/red_sox_to_turn.html|title=Red Sox to \"turn back the clock\" on Saturday against the Cubs|date=May 19, 2011|first=Michael|last=Vega|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n* In 2016, David Ortiz set all-time records for most home runs<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/17599694/david-ortiz-breaks-dave-kingman-final-season-hr-record-36th |title=David Ortiz breaks Dave Kingman's final-season HR record with 36th |first=Scott |last=Lauber |publisher=ESPN.com |date=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> and runs batted in<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/ortiz-sets-mark-for-most-rbis-in-final-season/2016/09/23/bb0042be-81f2-11e6-9578-558cc125c7ba_story.html |title=Ortiz sets mark for most RBIs in final season |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 23, 2016 |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> in a player's final MLB season. Ortiz finished the season with 38 homers, which surpassed [[Dave Kingman]]'s 35 in 1986, and 127 runs batted in, which surpassed [[Shoeless Joe Jackson]]'s 123 in 1920.\n*The Red Sox set a team record for wins in a regular season with 108 in 2018, surpassing the 106-year-old record of 105 wins set in 1912. Including playoffs, the Red Sox won a total of 119 games, the third most total wins in an MLB season. {{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n*On October 8, 2018, [[Brock Holt]] became the first player in MLB history to hit for the cycle in the postseason, doing so in a 16\u20131 win over the New York Yankees in [[2018 American League Division Series#Game 3, October 8|Game 3 of the 2018 American League Division Series]].<ref name=cycle2018>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/brock-holt-completes-the-first-playoff-cycle/c-297456294 |title=Brock Holt completes first postseason cycle |first=David |last=Adler |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=October 8, 2018 |accessdate=October 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Boston Red Sox all-time roster]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox team records]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox seasons]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox award winners]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox managers]]\n* [[List of Boston Red Sox coaches]]\n* [[List of World Series champions]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball franchise postseason streaks]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball franchise postseason droughts]]\n* [[Tony Conigliaro Award]]\n* [[The Jimmy Fund]]\n* ''[[Fever Pitch (2005 film)|Fever Pitch]]''&nbsp;\u2013 a film covering the 2004 Boston Red Sox championship run from a fan-based point of view.\n* ''[[Game 6 (film)|Game 6]]''&nbsp;\u2013 a film covering the Red Sox's ultimately unsuccessful 1986 World Series championship run.\n* ''[[Red Sox Rule]]'' \u2013 a 2008 book written by [[Michael Holley]].\n*[[Red Sox Song]]\n*[[Yankees\u2013Red Sox rivalry|Yankees-Red Sox Rivalry]] \n*[[List of Boston Red Sox managers|List of Boston Red Sox Managers]]\n*[[History of the Boston Red Sox]]\n*[[Red Sox Nation]]\n*[[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n*[[List of Boston Red Sox seasons|List of Boston Red Sox Seasons]]\n*[[2018 World Series]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n*{{Cite book|last=Nowlin|first=Bill|last2=Prime|first2=Jim|title=Feud: The Red Sox, The Yankees, and the Struggle of Good versus Evil|publisher=Rounder Books|year=2005|isbn=1-57940-111-2}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Stout|first=Glenn|last2=Johnson|first2=Richard A.|title=Red Sox Century|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|year=2000|isbn=0-395-88417-9}}\n*{{cite book|title=Red Sox vs. Yankees: The Great Rivalry|first=Harvey|last=Frommer|first2=Frederic J.|last2=Frommer|publisher=Sports Publishing, LLC|year=2004|isbn=1-58261-767-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Shaughnessy|