in/|East Tehran=http://iauet.ac.ir/fa}}\n{{International Council for Science}}\n{{coord|35.7328|N|51.3889|E|source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1982 establishments in Iran]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Islamic Azad University| ]]\n[[Category:Engineering universities and colleges in Iran]]\n[[Category:Universities in Tehran]]\n", "name_user": "Datwhitearab", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamic_Azad_University"}
{"title_page": "New Basford railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name      = New Basford\n|image_name= New Basford railway station (1961).jpg\n|caption   = \n|locale    = [[Basford, Nottingham|Basford]]\n|borough   = [[Nottingham]]\n|line      = \n|original  = [[Great Central Railway]] \n|postgroup = [[London and North Eastern Railway]][[British Railways]]\n|platforms = 2\n|gridref   = \n|years     = 15 March 1899\n|events    = Station opens    \n|years1    = 7 September 1964\n|events1   = Station closes  <ref name=\"Butt\">Butt, R.V.J. (1995). ''The Directory of Railway Stations'', Patrick Stephens Ltd, Sparkford, {{ISBN|1-85260-508-1}}, p. 43.</ref>  \n}}\n'''New Basford railway station''' was a station in [[Nottingham]] on the [[Great Central Railway]] [[Great Central Main Line|main line]],<ref>British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer.</ref> the last main line to be built from the north of England to London. The station opened with the line on 15 March 1899.\n\n==History==\nThe station was one of the standard island platform design typical of the [[Great Central Main Line|London Extension]], though here it was the less common \"embankment\" type reached from a roadway (Haydn Road), that passed beneath the line. A short distance to the south was Sherwood Rise Tunnel.\n\nAs well as handling local train services on the Great Central line itself, it was also served by [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] trains to [[Ilkeston]], [[Derby]], [[Uttoxeter]] and [[Stafford]], on their [[GNR Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension|Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension]], these trains branching off the Great Central about half a mile to the north at Bagthorpe Junction. Having running powers over this section of the Great Central line provided the Great Northern with the most direct route out of Nottingham for these trains, better than their own somewhat roundabout route via [[Daybrook railway station|Daybrook]].\n\nLocal passenger services on the Great Central line ceased on 4 March 1963 when most local stations closed, but New Basford remained open until 7 September 1964 as the former Great Northern services continued to run until then, although they had stopped operating beyond [[Derby Friargate railway station]] on 4 December 1939. Main line passenger traffic on the Great Central ceased on 5 September 1966; goods traffic to New Basford on 2 October 1967 and this section of the line closed completely on 25 March 1968.\n\nWhere New Basford station once stood is now a housing development, but the stationmaster's house still remains. \n \n{{Disused Rail Start}} \n{{rail line one to two |previous=[[Carrington railway station|Carrington]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next1=[[Bulwell Common railway station|Bulwell Common]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route1=[[Great Central Railway]]<br /><small>[[Great Central Main Line|London Extension]]</small> |col1={{GCR colour}}\n|next2=[[Basford and Bulwell railway station|Basford & Bulwell]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route2=[[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]<br /><small>[[GNR Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension|(Derby) Friargate Line]]</small> |col2={{GNR colour}} }}\n{{end box}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|52.9782|-1.1635|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Closed Stations Nottinghamshire}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1899]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Beeching closures in England]]\n\n\n{{EastMidlands-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name      = New Basford\n|image_name= New Basford railway station (1961).jpg\n|caption   = \n|locale    = [[Basford, Nottingham|Basford]]\n|borough   = [[Nottingham]]\n|line      = \n|original  = [[Great Central Railway]] \n|postgroup = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]br[[British Railways]]\n|platforms = 2\n|gridref   = \n|years     = 15 March 1899\n|events    = Station opens    \n|years1    = 7 September 1964\n|events1   = Station closes  <ref name=\"Butt\">Butt, R.V.J. (1995). ''The Directory of Railway Stations'', Patrick Stephens Ltd, Sparkford, {{ISBN|1-85260-508-1}}, p. 43.</ref>  \n}}\n'''New Basford railway station''' was a station in [[Nottingham]] on the [[Great Central Railway]] [[Great Central Main Line|main line]],<ref>British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer.</ref> the last main line to be built from the north of England to London. The station opened with the line on 15 March 1899.\n\n==History==\nThe station was one of the standard island platform design typical of the [[Great Central Main Line|London Extension]], though here it was the less common \"embankment\" type reached from a roadway (Haydn Road), that passed beneath the line. A short distance to the south was Sherwood Rise Tunnel.\n\nAs well as handling local train services on the Great Central line itself, it was also served by [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] trains to [[Ilkeston]], [[Derby]], [[Uttoxeter]] and [[Stafford]], on their [[GNR Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension|Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension]], these trains branching off the Great Central about half a mile to the north at Bagthorpe Junction. Having running powers over this section of the Great Central line provided the Great Northern with the most direct route out of Nottingham for these trains, better than their own somewhat roundabout route via [[Daybrook railway station|Daybrook]].\n\nLocal passenger services on the Great Central line ceased on 4 March 1963 when most local stations closed, but New Basford remained open until 7 September 1964 as the former Great Northern services continued to run until then, although they had stopped operating beyond [[Derby Friargate railway station]] on 4 December 1939. Main line passenger traffic on the Great Central ceased on 5 September 1966; goods traffic to New Basford on 2 October 1967 and this section of the line closed completely on 25 March 1968.\n\nWhere New Basford station once stood is now a housing development, but the stationmaster's house still remains. \n \n{{Disused Rail Start}} \n{{rail line one to two |previous=[[Carrington railway station|Carrington]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next1=[[Bulwell Common railway station|Bulwell Common]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route1=[[Great Central Railway]]<br /><small>[[Great Central Main Line|London Extension]]</small> |col1={{GCR colour}}\n|next2=[[Basford and Bulwell railway station|Basford & Bulwell]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route2=[[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]<br /><small>[[GNR Derbyshire and Staffordshire Extension|(Derby) Friargate Line]]</small> |col2={{GNR colour}} }}\n{{end box}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|52.9782|-1.1635|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Closed Stations Nottinghamshire}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1899]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Beeching closures in England]]\n\n\n{{EastMidlands-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Steamybrian2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Basford_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Let Me Love You (Mario song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|2004 single by Mario}}\n{{About|the 2004 song written by Ne-Yo|Ne-Yo's 2012 similarly titled song|Let Me Love You (Until You Learn to Love Yourself)|other uses|Let Me Love You (disambiguation){{!}}Let Me Love You}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Let Me Love You\n| cover      = Mario-let me love you.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mario (American singer)|Mario]]\n| album      = [[Turning Point (Mario album)|Turning Point]]\n| B-side     = Call Out Hook\n| released   = {{start date|2004|07|8}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[12-inch single|12-inch]]|[[CD single|CD]]|digital download}}\n| recorded   = 2004\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:09\n| label      = {{hlist|[[J Records|J]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Ne-Yo|Shaffer Smith]]|Kameron Houff|Scott Storch}}\n| producer   = Scott Storch\n| prev_title = [[C'Mon (Mario song)|C'mon]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[How Could You (Mario song)|How Could You]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n| misc       = \n}}\n\"'''Let Me Love You'''\" is a song by American singer [[Mario (American singer)|Mario]]. It was released in 2004 from his second studio album, ''[[Turning Point (Mario album)|Turning Point]]'' (2004). It was written by [[Ne-Yo]], Kameron Houff and [[Scott Storch]], and produced by Storch. The [[remix]] of the song, also produced by Storch, contains [[Rapping|rapped]] verses from [[Jadakiss]] and [[T.I.]]. The song was an instant hit, garnering Mario a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best Male R&B Vocal Performance]] in 2006.\n\nIn 2008, it was ranked at number 45 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s All-Time Top 100 Hot 100 singles during the first 50 years of the chart.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-50.shtml The Billboard Hot 100 All-Time Top Songs (50\u201341)]</ref> It was the eighth most successful single of the decade according to the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 Songs of the Decade chart released in December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/chart_display.jsp?g=Singles&f=Greece#/../../charts-decade-end/hot-100-songs?year=2009|title=Charts}}</ref> In 2013, it was ranked at number 53 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s All-Time Top 100 Hot 100 singles during the first 55 years of the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/2155531/the-hot-100-all-time-top-songs?list_page=4|title=Hot 100 55th Anniversary: The All-Time Top 100 Songs}}</ref>\n\nDutch producer Dastic sampled the song and released his own [[tropical house]] version featuring vocals from singer CADE. The version charted on the [[Ultratop|Belgian]] Dance and Ultratip Bubbling Under charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/18949f/Dastic-feat.-CADE-Let-Me-Love-You|title=Dastic feat. CADE \u2013 Let Me Love You|website=ultratop.be|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music and structure==\n\"Let Me Love You\" is a moderate R&B ballad in [[G minor]], centered around the progression C minor / G minor / F major. It is written in [[common time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/download/scorch/default.asp?ppn=SC0022946|title=Download Sheet Music Software \u2013 Musicnotes.com}}</ref> The song was written by [[Ne-Yo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=18346 |title=R.-Kelly's one night stand |author=[[Jasmine Dotiwala]] |newspaper=Voice Online |date=October 28, 2010 |quote=Let Me Love You at the time that I wrote it I wasn't trying to be an artist, I was completely content with just being a song writer but I think back on that song and I look back and think had I been trying to be an artist at the time that's definitely one I would have held on to. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130095518/http://voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=18346 |archivedate=November 30, 2010}}</ref> and features him singing backing vocals in two-part harmony and unison.\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\nJon Pareles from ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented that \"Let Me Love You\" \"looks back to another 1980s blockbuster, lifting its keyboard sound from [[Tina Turner]]'s '[[What's Love Got to Do with It (song)|What's Love Got to Do with It]]'.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/20/arts/20choi.html|title=CRITIC'S CHOICE New CD's | work=The New York Times | first=Jon | last=Pareles | date=December 20, 2004 | accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades and nominations===\nIn 2004, \"Let Me Love You\" was nominated for a [[Vibe Awards|Vibe Award]] for Best R&B Song and two [[Teen Choice Awards]], [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Music \u2013 Love Song|Choice Love Song]] and Choice R&B/Rap Track, but it failed to receive any awards. In 2005, it received nominations for [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], including \"Hot 100 Single of the Year\", \"Hot 100 Airplay Single of the Year\", \"Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Single of the Year\", \"Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay Single of the Year, winning in both the R&B categories. It was also nominated for an MTV Europe Music Award for Best R&B Single, a Viewer's Choice award at the [[BET Awards]], Best Single at the [[MOBO Awards]], and Best R&B/Soul Song at the [[Soul Train Music Awards]]. In 2006, Mario was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best Male R&B Vocal Performance]] with \"Let Me Love You\". He also received an [[MTV Australia Awards]] nomination for Best R&B music video for \"Let Me Love You\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/factsheets/awardsdb/env-awards-db-search,0,7169155.htmlstory?searchtype=person&query=Mario|title= Mario 2005 BET Awards,Teen Choice Awards & Billboard Music Awards|accessdate=January 18, 2009 | work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/awards/a/billboardma2005_2.htm|title=Billboard Music Award Nominations 2005|accessdate=January 25, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/61860/usher-50-cent-lead-billboard-rbhip-hop-winners |title=Usher, 50 Cent Lead Billboard R&B/Hip-Hop Winners |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922061403/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/61860/usher-50-cent-lead-billboard-rbhip-hop-winners |archivedate=September 22, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 18, 2009|url= http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-m/mario.htm|title= Mario grammy nominations|publisher=Rock on the Net}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4273504.stm\n|title= Mobo awards 2005: The winners|publisher=BBC|accessdate=January 18, 2009 | date=September 22, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvasia.com/News/200602/10013165.html |title=The Darkness and the Veronicas Set To Perform at the 2006 MTV Australia Video Music Awards |accessdate=January 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222184152/http://www.mtvasia.com/News/200602/10013165.html |archivedate=February 22, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-02-01-soul-train-awards_x.htm|title=Usher gets five Soul Train nominations | work=USA Today | date=February 2, 2005 | accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=  http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2005/10/vibe_announces_2005_vibe_award_nominees/|title=  VIBE Announces 2005 VIBE Award Nominees|accessdate=  January 18, 2009|url-status=  dead|archiveurl=  https://web.archive.org/web/20081204191710/http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2005/10/vibe_announces_2005_vibe_award_nominees/|archivedate=  December 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Let Me Love You\" debuted on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100 the week of October 23, 2004 at number 97. The song went on to hold the number-one position on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart for nine consecutive weeks from January to February 2005, and, as of 2019, is Mario's biggest single. It also reached number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart. Internationally, it reached the number-one position on the singles charts in Germany, the Netherlands, and New Zealand. In the United Kingdom, the song reached number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]] (held off the top spot by \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo]]\"), making it Mario's biggest hit to date in the UK. The single also holds the honor of being one of the highest-selling ringtones with 1.6&nbsp;million downloads.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mario2u.com/biography|title=Mario \u2013 Top selling ringtones|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316000930/http://www.mario2u.com/biography|archivedate=March 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n{{Expand section|more details|date=March 2017}}\nThe music video was directed by [[Little X]]. As of 2020 it has 250+ million views on YouTube.\n\n==Covers==\n* [[Charlotte Church]] covered the song as a B-side to her \"[[Call My Name (Charlotte Church song)|Call My Name]]\" single.\n* The [[Glee cast|cast]] of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' covered the song in the [[Glee (season 3)|season 3]] episode \"[[Heart (Glee)|Heart]]\".\n* [[Zayn Malik]] from [[One Direction]] sang the song at his audition for ''[[The X Factor]]'' in 2010.\n* DJ/producer Fei-Fei sampled some of the vocals for her track \"Back To You\"\n* [[Austin Mahone]] and [[Justin Bieber]] each covered the song at the start of their careers.\n* Indonesian singer Widi Winata covered the song in 2014.\n* [[Mario (American singer)|Mario]] and [[Zendaya]] performed the song on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Greatest Hits (TV series)|Greatest Hits]]'' in 2016 (season 1, episode 5).\n* [[Country pop]] artist [[Chris Lane]] recorded a cover version of the song for his debut studio album, ''[[Girl Problems]]''.\n* ''[[The Voice Nigeria]]'' contestants [[Chike]] and Patrick from team [[Patoranking]] did a cover version of the song for their battle round in 2016.\n* American rapper [[6ix9ine]] sampled the first verse of the song on his 2018 single \"SESE\".\n\n==Track listing==\n'''US CD single'''\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (album version)\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (remix version)\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (Mauve Remix Extended)\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (video)\n\n'''US promo CD'''\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (album version)\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (Mauve Remix Edit)\n\n'''Australian CD single'''\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (album version)\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (remix version)\n# \"Whiz\"\n# Multimedia track\n\n'''12-inch maxi single'''\n# \"Let Me Love You\"\n# \"Let Me Love You\" (instrumental)\n# \"Call Out Hook\"\n\n'''Remix'''\n# \"Let Me Love You\" {{small|(featuring [[Jadakiss]] and [[T.I.]])}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2004\u201305)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Australia|3|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Austria|6|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Flanders|3|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Wallonia|12|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n|Czech Republic ([[IFPI]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed \u010cesk\u00e1 Hitpar\u00e1da - Pro t\u00fdden|url=http://www.ifpicr.cz/radio.htm|publisher=IFPI \u010cR|language=Czech|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050601074009/http://www.ifpicr.cz:80/radio.htm|archivedate=June 1, 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|46\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Denmark|2|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_BQEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=RA1-PA65&vq=ciara%20eurochart&lr&rview=1&pg=RA1-PA65#v=onepage&q=ciara%20eurochart&f=false|title=Eurocharts|magazine=[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]|volume=117|issue=17|page=65|date=April 30, 2005|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Finland|16|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|France|7|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Germany|1|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Hungary|18|year=2005|week=20}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Ireland2|5|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Italy|2|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Dutch40|1|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Dutch100|2|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|New Zealand|1|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Norway|5|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Scotland|4|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You|date=April 2, 2005}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Spain|18|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Sweden|18|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Swiss|2|artist=Mario|song=Let Me Love You}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|UK|2|date=20050402}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|UKrandb|1|date=20050227}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Mario|accessdate=September 22, 2014}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|1|artist=Mario|accessdate=September 22, 2014}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|1|artist=Mario|accessdate=September 22, 2014}}\n|-\n|US [[Pop 100]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{allmusic|class=artist|tab=awards|title=Mario > Awards |id=mn0000274637|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|1|artist=Mario|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2005)\n!Position\n|-\n|Australia ([[ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ariacharts.com.au/annual-charts/2005/singles-chart|title=2005 Annual ARIA Singles Chart|publisher=Australian Rec