p 40 number-one songs of 2005]]\n*[[List of number-one R&B singles of 2005 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|mario|let-me-love-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Mario}}\n\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n[[Category:2004 songs]]\n[[Category:2004 singles]]\n[[Category:2005 singles]]\n[[Category:Mario (American singer) songs]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B ballads]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK R&B Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ne-Yo]]\n[[Category:Torch songs]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: on 2004 \u2192 in 2004", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Let_Me_Love_You_(Mario_song)"}
{"title_page": "Choe Pu-il", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Choe}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul  = \ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c\n| hanja   = \u5d14\u5bcc\u65e5\n| rr      = Choe Buil\n| mr      = Ch'oe Puil\n| context = north\n| image   = \n| caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Choe Pu-il\n|native_name  = \ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c\n|image        =\n|office       = Minister of People's Security\n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|president    = \n|term_start   = 2013\n|term_end     = February 2020\n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|office1      = \n|president1    = \n|term_start1   = \n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = \n|successor1    = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\nGeneral '''Choe Pu-il''' ({{lang|ko|\ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c}}; born 6 March 1944<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=23 March 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=2593 |language=ko  }}</ref>) is the current head of [[North Korea]]'s [[Ministry of Public Security (North Korea)|Ministry of People's Security]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=April 1, 2013 |title=N. Korea appoints new security chief |url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/search1/2603000000.html?cid=AEN20130401002900315 |newspaper=[[Yonhap]] |location=Seoul |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 28, 2013 |title=President of Mongolia meets with Minister of People's Security of the National Defense Commission of North Korea |url=http://www.infomongolia.com/ct/ci/6568 |newspaper=InfoMongolia.com |location= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn April 1992, he was promoted to Major General and to General in October 1995. After serving as Deputy Chief of the [[General Staff Department of the Korean People's Army|General Staff]] the [[Korean People's Army]], he served as First Deputy Chief of Staff and Chief of Operations of the General Staff. He became a member of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Military Commission]] of the Party at the [[3rd Conference of the Workers' Party of Korea]] held in September 2010. In the same month, along with Kim Jong-un, [[Kim Kyong-hui]], [[Choe Ryong-hae]], and [[Hyon Yong-chol]], he received the military rank of [[General of the Army]]. He served as a commander at the April 2012 servicing ceremony, where Kim Jong-un gave his first speech.\n\nHe was appointed to the [[Minister of People's Security]] in February 2013 by [[Kim Jong-un]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kang |first=Mi-jin |date=June 11, 2013 |title=Kim \"Repromotes\" Choi Bu Il |url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=10642 |newspaper=[[Daily NK]] |location=Seoul |access-date= }}</ref> and was elected as a candidate for the [[Central Committee]] full meeting on March 31, 2013. He was elected as a member of the National Defense Commission.\n\nHe was [[2014 North Korean parliamentary election|elected delegate]] in the election to the 13th [[Supreme People's Assembly]]. On May 17, it was reported that he had visited a site of a collapsed high-rise apartment in the Pyongyang area of \u200b\u200bPyongyang City and apologized to the bereaved family members and residents along with senior government officials. In December of the same year, it was confirmed that Choi had been demoted to Major General. In October 2015, it was confirmed that Choi was again promoted to a General rank.\n\nIn July 2016, he was placed under sanctions by the United States government.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brunnstrom|first1=David|last2=Pearson|first2=James|title=North Korea warns of tough response after U.S. blacklisted leader|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-sanctions-report/north-korea-warns-of-tough-response-after-u-s-blacklisted-leader-idUSKCN0ZM1O3|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=27 November 2017|date=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 he was replaced by [[Kim Jong-ho]].<ref>[https://cn.yna.co.kr/view/ACK20200213004900881 \u671d\u9c9c\u4eba\u6c11\u4fdd\u5b89\u76f8\u6362\u4eba \u5f00\u57ce\u5347\u683c\u4e3a\u7279\u522b\u5e02]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Ri Myong-su]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of People's Security|Minister of People's Security]]|years=February 2013-February 2020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Jong-ho]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choe, Pu-il}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in North Korea]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n{{NorthKorea-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Choe}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul  = \ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c\n| hanja   = \u5d14\u5bcc\u65e5\n| rr      = Choe Buil\n| mr      = Ch'oe Puil\n| context = north\n| image   = \n| caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Choe Pu-il\n|native_name  = \ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c\n|image        =\n|office       = Minister of People's Security\n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|president    = \n|term_start   = 2013\n|term_end     = February 2020\n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|office1      = \n|president1    = \n|term_start1   = \n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = \n|successor1    = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\nGeneral '''Choe Pu-il''' ({{lang|ko|\ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c}}; born 6 March 1944<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\ucd5c\ubd80\uc77c(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=23 March 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=2593 |language=ko  }}</ref>) is the current head of [[North Korea]]'s [[Ministry of Public Security (North Korea)|Ministry of People's Security]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=April 1, 2013 |title=N. Korea appoints new security chief |url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/search1/2603000000.html?cid=AEN20130401002900315 |newspaper=[[Yonhap]] |location=Seoul |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 28, 2013 |title=President of Mongolia meets with Minister of People's Security of the National Defense Commission of North Korea |url=http://www.infomongolia.com/ct/ci/6568 |newspaper=InfoMongolia.com |location= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIn April 1992, he was promoted to Major General and to General in October 1995. After serving as Deputy Chief of the [[General Staff Department of the Korean People's Army|General Staff]] the [[Korean People's Army]], he served as First Deputy Chief of Staff and Chief of Operations of the General Staff. He became a member of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Military Commission]] of the Party at the [[3rd Conference of the Workers' Party of Korea]] held in September 2010. In the same month, along with Kim Jong-un, [[Kim Kyong-hui]], [[Choe Ryong-hae]], and [[Hyon Yong-chol]], he received the military rank of [[General of the Army]]. He served as a commander at the April 2012 servicing ceremony, where Kim Jong-un gave his first speech.\n\nHe was appointed to the [[Minister of People's Security]] in February 2013 by [[Kim Jong-un]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kang |first=Mi-jin |date=June 11, 2013 |title=Kim \"Repromotes\" Choi Bu Il |url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=10642 |newspaper=[[Daily NK]] |location=Seoul |access-date= }}</ref> and was elected as a candidate for the [[Central Committee]] full meeting on March 31, 2013. He was elected as a member of the National Defense Commission.\n\nHe was [[2014 North Korean parliamentary election|elected delegate]] in the election to the 13th [[Supreme People's Assembly]]. On May 17, it was reported that he had visited a site of a collapsed high-rise apartment in the Pyongyang area of \u200b\u200bPyongyang City and apologized to the bereaved family members and residents along with senior government officials. In December of the same year, it was confirmed that Choi had been demoted to Major General. In October 2015, it was confirmed that Choi was again promoted to a General rank.\n\nIn July 2016, he was placed under sanctions by the United States government.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brunnstrom|first1=David|last2=Pearson|first2=James|title=North Korea warns of tough response after U.S. blacklisted leader|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-sanctions-report/north-korea-warns-of-tough-response-after-u-s-blacklisted-leader-idUSKCN0ZM1O3|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=27 November 2017|date=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 he was replaced by [[Kim Jong-ho]].<ref>[https://cn.yna.co.kr/view/ACK20200213004900881 \u671d\u9c9c\u4eba\u6c11\u4fdd\u5b89\u76f8\u6362\u4eba \u5f00\u57ce\u5347\u683c\u4e3a\u7279\u522b\u5e02]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choe, Pu-il}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in North Korea]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n{{NorthKorea-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choe_Pu-il"}
{"title_page": "S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport\n| nativename   = S. Dariaus ir S. Gir\u0117no aerodromas\n| IATA         = \n| ICAO         = EYKS\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = \n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[Kaunas]], [[Lithuania]]\n| location     = [[Aleksotas]]\n| elevation-f  = 246\n| elevation-m  = 75\n| coordinates  = {{coord|54|52|48|N|023|52|54|E|type:airport}}\n| website      = \n| metric-rwy   = y\n| r1-number    = 09R/27L\n| r1-length-m  = 1,130\n| r1-length-f  = 3,707\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| footnotes    = \n| image        = Approaching_Aleksotas_Airport_(EYKS)_Runway_27.JPG\n}}\n\n'''S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport''' (''S. Dariaus ir S. Gir\u0117no aerodromas'') {{airport codes||EYKS}}, also known as '''Aleksotas Airport''' (''Aleksoto aerodromas''), is a small [[airport]] located in [[Aleksotas]] district of [[Kaunas]] City ([[Lithuania]]), about 3 kilometres South-west from city centre. On May 6, 1993, the airport was named after the Lithuanian pilots [[Steponas Darius]] and [[Stasys Gir\u0117nas]], who perished in a crash near the end of an [[Lituanica#Flight|attempted non-stop flight from New York to Lithuania]] in 1933.\n\n==Military use==\n\nS. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport was conceived as military [[airport]], established by [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]] in 1915, after it captured [[Kaunas Fortress]]. Used continuously since then it is the oldest functioning airport in Lithuania, making it also one of the oldest airports in [[Europe]]. The airport area underwent major upgrades in 1926, 1931, 1942 (800 m. concrete runway with taxiways, repair hangars built), 1950's (concrete runway extension to 1330 m.) and 1970's (passenger terminal, navigation equipment).\n\nDuring the [[Interwar period]], when Kaunas was Lithuania's capital, Aleksotas Airport was used as primary base of Lithuanian Air Force. It also served as test ground for locally built airplanes, like [[Dobi I]], [[Dobi II]], [[Dobi III]] by [[Jurgis Dobkevi\u010dius]], [[Anbo I]], [[Anbo II]], [[Anbo III]], [[Anbo IV]] and [[Anbo 41]], [[Anbo V]], [[Anbo VI]], [[Anbo VII]] and [[Anbo VIII]] by [[Antanas Gustaitis]], gliders.<ref>[[List of Lithuanian gliders]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe airport suffered heavily during World War II. On June 22, 1941, [[Luftwaffe]] on the ground destroyed most of [[Red Army]] aircraft, stationed in Aleksotas Airfield. Airport infrastructure suffered major damage in July 1944 during the battle for Kaunas. Retreating [[Wehrmacht]] destroyed most of the hangars, and heavily damaged runway and taxiways.\n\nIn 1940-1941 and in 1944-1993 it was used as a Soviet (1991-1993 - Russian) airbase, in 1941-1944 as a German Luftwaffe base. Soviet Air Force used Aleksotas Airport as military transport and military helicopter base, with stationed [[Mil Mi-2]], [[Mil Mi-6]] and [[Mil Mi-8]] helicopters prior to its full withdrawal in August 1993.\n\nOn May 20, 2016, Lithuanian Air Force moved its Second Search and Rescue post (three helicopter landing areas, one helicopter on constant duty) from [[Freda Airfield]] (Kaunas Aviation Plant airfield, EYKG)<ref>[[:lt:Kauno aviacijos gamyklos aerodromas]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}} to Aleksotas Airport.\n\n==Civil air communication==\n\nThe civil air communication was started by the German airlines in 1921. Initially the mail and passenger line [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]-[[Kaunas]] was served by [[Lloyd Luftdienst]], [[Danziger Luftdienst]], [[Danziger Luftpost]]. German-Soviet airline [[Deruluft]] airline opened regular service [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]-Kaunas-[[Smolensk]]-[[Moscow]] in May 1922. This was later expanded to the route [[Berlin]]-[[Gda\u0144sk|Danzig]]-K\u00f6nigsberg-Kaunas-Smolensk-Moscow. In 1923-1925 Latvian airline [[Latvijas Gaisa Satiksmes Akciju Sabiedriba|Latvijas Gaisa Satiksmes AS]] operated K\u00f6nigsberg-Kaunas-Riga-Tallinn-Helsinki route, with the latter being closed in 1925 due to low profitability and withdrawal of Latvian government subsidies. Since 1938 Polish airline LOT operated flights on the route [[Warsaw]]-Kaunas-[[Riga]]-[[Helsinki]], also connecting with Stockholm{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}.\n\nIn 1931 the first passenger terminal was built, it was destroyed during World War II. A new Terminal was built in the 1970s{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}.\n\nAleksotas airport was the base of the first Lithuanian airline: the national airline [[Lietuvos oro linijos]] was founded in 1938, when Lithuanian government ordered two British-built twin engine six-seat planes [[Percival Petrel|Percival Q 6 Petrel]]. The planes were registered LY-SOA and LY-SOB and, commemorating the national trans-Atlantic heroes, were respectively named \"Steponas Darius\" and \"Stasys Gir\u0117nas\". The first Lithuanian civil airline was inaugurated on 5 September 1938 with domestic flights from Kaunas (the country's provisional capital at that time) to the coastal resort of [[Palanga]]. Later in 1939 ''Lietuvos oro linijos'' launched international flights to Riga (Latvia).<ref>http://www.sumin.lt/en/activities/sectors_activities The Ministry of Transport and Communications of Lithuania. Civil Aviation</ref>\n\nAll international connections were disrupted on June 16, 1940 when the airport was captured by the Red Army. Civil flights to Moscow were launched at the end of 1940 after the formal integration of Lithuania into the Soviet Union.\n\nIn the early 1950s regular civilian connections with other towns (but then only within USSR) were opened. Due to a short runway and limited extension possibilities the airport could accept only a very limited number of jet aircraft types. In the 1980s, Aleksotas Airport was considered one of the most dangerous airports in Europe due to its short runway.<ref>http://vyrud.livejournal.com/100565.html LiveJournal. Kaunas Aleksotas airport</ref> It is claimed that only one type of jet - the [[Yak-40]] - could use this airport. Even so, in the 1980s it was a base for about 15 Yak planes, connecting with nearly 30 cities within the USSR, as far as Odessa and Simferopol{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}. Regular passenger flights in Aleksotas airport were stopped in 1988 and were moved to a new [[Kaunas Airport|Kaunas International Airport]] in Karm\u0117lava at the northeastern outskirts of Kaunas. Paradoxically, the opening of the new airport coincided with long term decrease in the number of connections from Kaunas: the new airport had limited passenger facilities and the economic downturn of the early 1990s resulted in a significant overall reduction of air communication.\n\nAfter the withdrawal of the Russian Air Force in 1993, Aleksotas / S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport serves general aviation. The airport hosts the Kaunas Air Club.\n\nIts historical importance makes it a natural host for the [[Lithuanian Aviation Museum]]. The old passenger terminal building was transferred to Aviation Museum on February 19, 1990.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Steponas Darius]] and [[Stasys Gir\u0117nas]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links, sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091106230345/http://www.aerokaunas.lt/english/ Kaunas Aeroclub]\n*[https://archive.is/20060619105008/http://193.219.160.44/aerokaunas/  S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Aviation Club in Aleksotas]\n*[http://www.lam.lt/ Lithuanian Aviation Museum]\n*[http://www.flyingineurope.be/pageyks.htm Peter's Airport Guide]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:S. Darius and S. Girenas Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Aviation in Kaunas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kaunas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport\n| nativename   = S. Dariaus ir S. Gir\u0117no aerodromas\n| IATA         = \n| ICAO         = EYKS\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = \n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[Kaunas]], [[Lithuania]]\n| location     = [[Aleksotas]]\n| elevation-f  = 246\n| elevation-m  = 75\n| coordinates  = {{coord|54|52|48|N|023|52|54|E|type:airport}}\n| website      = \n| metric-rwy   = y\n| r1-number    = 09R/27L\n| r1-length-m  = 1,130\n| r1-length-f  = 3,707\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| footnotes    = \n| image        = Approaching_Aleksotas_Airport_(EYKS)_Runway_27.JPG\n}}\n\n'''S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport''' (''S. Dariaus ir S. Gir\u0117no aerodromas'') {{airport codes||EYKS}}, also known as '''Aleksotas Airport''' (''Aleksoto aerodromas''), is a small [[airport]] located in [[Aleksotas]] district of [[Kaunas]] City ([[Lithuania]]), about 3 kilometres South-west from city centre. On May 6, 1993, the airport was named after the Lithuanian pilots [[Steponas Darius]] and [[Stasys Gir\u0117nas]], who perished in a crash near the end of an [[Lituanica#Flight|attempted non-stop flight from New York to Lithuania]] in 1933.\n\n==Military use==\n\nS. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport was conceived as military [[airport]], established by [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]] in 1915, after it captured [[Kaunas Fortress]]. Used continuously since then it is the oldest functioning airport in Lithuania, making it also one of the oldest airports in [[Europe]]. The airport area underwent major upgrades in 1926, 1931, 1942 (800 m. concrete runway with taxiways, repair hangars built), 1950's (concrete runway extension to 1330 m.) and 1970's (passenger terminal, navigation equipment).\n\nDuring the [[Interwar period]], when Kaunas was Lithuania's capital, Aleksotas Airport was used as primary base of Lithuanian Air Force. It also served as test ground for locally built airplanes, like [[Dobi I]], [[Dobi II]], [[Dobi III]] by [[Jurgis Dobkevi\u010dius]], [[Anbo I]], [[Anbo II]], [[Anbo III]], [[Anbo IV]] and [[Anbo 41]], [[Anbo V]], [[Anbo VI]], [[Anbo VII]] and [[Anbo VIII]] by [[Antanas Gustaitis]], gliders.<ref>[[List of Lithuanian gliders]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe airport suffered heavily during World War II. On June 22, 1941, [[Luftwaffe]] on the ground destroyed most of [[Red Army]] aircraft, stationed in Aleksotas Airfield. Airport infrastructure suffered major damage in July 1944 during the battle for Kaunas. Retreating [[Wehrmacht]] destroyed most of the hangars, and heavily damaged runway and taxiways.\n\nIn 1940-1941 and in 1944-1993 it was used as a Soviet (1991-1993 - Russian) airbase, in 1941-1944 as a German Luftwaffe base. Soviet Air Force used Aleksotas Airport as military transport and military helicopter base, with stationed [[Mil Mi-2]], [[Mil Mi-6]] and [[Mil Mi-8]] helicopters prior to its full withdrawal in August 1993.\n\nOn May 20, 2016, Lithuanian Air Force moved its Second Search and Rescue post (three helicopter landing areas, one helicopter on constant duty) from [[Freda Airfield]] (Kaunas Aviation Plant airfield, EYKG)<ref>[[:lt:Kauno aviacijos gamyklos aerodromas]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}} to Aleksotas Airport.\n\n==Civil air communication==\n\nThe civil air communication was started by the German airlines in 1921. Initially the mail and passenger line [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]-[[Kaunas]] was served by [[Lloyd Luftdienst]], [[Danziger Luftdienst]], [[Danziger Luftpost]]. German-Soviet airline [[Deruluft]] airline opened regular service [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]-Kaunas-[[Smolensk]]-[[Moscow]] in May 1922. This was later expanded to the route [[Berlin]]-[[Gda\u0144sk|Danzig]]-K\u00f6nigsberg-Kaunas-Smolensk-Moscow. In 1923-1925 Latvian airline [[Latvijas Gaisa Satiksme AS]] operated K\u00f6nigsberg-Kaunas-Riga-Tallinn-Helsinki route, with the latter being closed in 1925 due to low profitability and withdrawal of Latvian government subsidies. Since 1938 Polish airline LOT operated flights on the route [[Warsaw]]-Kaunas-[[Riga]]-[[Helsinki]], also connecting with Stockholm{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}.\n\nIn 1931 the first passenger terminal was built, it was destroyed during World War II. A new Terminal was built in the 1970s{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}.\n\nAleksotas airport was the base of the first Lithuanian airline: the national airline [[Lietuvos oro linijos]] was founded in 1938, when Lithuanian government ordered two British-built twin engine six-seat planes [[Percival Petrel|Percival Q 6 Petrel]]. The planes were registered LY-SOA and LY-SOB and, commemorating the national trans-Atlantic heroes, were respectively named \"Steponas Darius\" and \"Stasys Gir\u0117nas\". The first Lithuanian civil airline was inaugurated on 5 September 1938 with domestic flights from Kaunas (the country's provisional capital at that time) to the coastal resort of [[Palanga]]. Later in 1939 ''Lietuvos oro linijos'' launched international flights to Riga (Latvia).<ref>http://www.sumin.lt/en/activities/sectors_activities The Ministry of Transport and Communications of Lithuania. Civil Aviation</ref>\n\nAll international connections were disrupted on June 16, 1940 when the airport was captured by the Red Army. Civil flights to Moscow were launched at the end of 1940 after the formal integration of Lithuania into the Soviet Union.\n\nIn the early 1950s regular civilian connections with other towns (but then only within USSR) were opened. Due to a short runway and limited extension possibilities the airport could accept only a very limited number of jet aircraft types. In the 1980s, Aleksotas Airport was considered one of the most dangerous airports in Europe due to its short runway.<ref>http://vyrud.livejournal.com/100565.html LiveJournal. Kaunas Aleksotas airport</ref> It is claimed that only one type of jet - the [[Yak-40]] - could use this airport. Even so, in the 1980s it was a base for about 15 Yak planes, connecting with nearly 30 cities within the USSR, as far as Odessa and Simferopol{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}. Regular passenger flights in Aleksotas airport were stopped in 1988 and were moved to a new [[Kaunas Airport|Kaunas International Airport]] in Karm\u0117lava at the northeastern outskirts of Kaunas. Paradoxically, the opening of the new airport coincided with long term decrease in the number of connections from Kaunas: the new airport had limited passenger facilities and the economic downturn of the early 1990s resulted in a significant overall reduction of air communication.\n\nAfter the withdrawal of the Russian Air Force in 1993, Aleksotas / S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Airport serves general aviation. The airport hosts the Kaunas Air Club.\n\nIts historical importance makes it a natural host for the [[Lithuanian Aviation Museum]]. The old passenger terminal building was transferred to Aviation Museum on February 19, 1990.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Steponas Darius]] and [[Stasys Gir\u0117nas]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links, sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091106230345/http://www.aerokaunas.lt/english/ Kaunas Aeroclub]\n*[https://archive.is/20060619105008/http://193.219.160.44/aerokaunas/  S. Darius and S. Gir\u0117nas Aviation Club in Aleksotas]\n*[http://www.lam.lt/ Lithuanian Aviation Museum]\n*[http://www.flyingineurope.be/pageyks.htm Peter's Airport Guide]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:S. Darius and S. Girenas Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Aviation in Kaunas]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kaunas]]\n", "name_user": "ArunasG", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCivil air communication:I have added one link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S._Darius_and_S._Gir%C4%97nas_Airport"}
